

for enumerating samba users and shares we can use

enum4linux:

	sudo enum4linux -U -S 10.10.38.248


nmap script engine

* Reference: nmap.org/nsedoc

			 --script=smb-enum-shares.nse
			 --script=smb-enum-sessions.nse
			 --script=smb-enum-services.nse
			 --script=smb-enum-domains.nse
			 --script=smb-enum-groups.nse

	sudo nmap -p 445 --script=smb-enum-shares-nse,smb-enum-users.nse <ip_addres>

** Usually SMB runs on port 445 (old versions 119) on top of a TCP stack which allows SMB to work over the internet.
---

for listing the shares of the smb server
 
	smbclient -N -L //ip_address/

for looking for the files inside one share of the smb server

	smbclient -N //ip_address/share

** -N means anonymous login, but sometimes we will need to bring a user and a password ( if anon log is not active)

------

for getting files from a sbm share we can do: (if anonymous log is on we wont need a password)

if we are logged in smb //<ip_add>/share

	ftp> get file.xx

or
	smbget -R smb://<ip_addres>/share




